│ THOUGHT: I can see the issue now. On line 1450, the code creates an `APInt MaxElts(IntWidth, NumElements)` where `IntWidth` is the bit width of the index type, but `NumElements`     │
│ might be larger than what can be represented in `IntWidth` bits. For example, in the first test case, we have a vector of 16 elements with an i1 index type (1 bit), but 16 cannot be │
│ represented in 1 bit (max value is 1). Similarly, in the second test case, we have 256 elements with i8 index (8 bits), but 256 requires 9 bits to represent (since 2^8 = 256, the    │
│ max representable value in 8 bits is 255). The APInt constructor correctly asserts this violation. The fix should check if `NumElements` can fit in `IntWidth` bits before creating   │
│ the APInt.                                                                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                       │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                               │
│ sed -i '1448a\  // Check if NumElements can be represented in IntWidth bits\n  if (!isUIntN(IntWidth, NumElements))\n    return ScalarizationResult::unsafe();'                       │
│ ./llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp                                                                                                                                     │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                   │
